\begin_layout Section
Effect of Vaccines (GOOD) :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Most of research have pointed out: due to the introduction of vaccination
 programs, the morbidity and mortality associated with the infectious diseases
 decreased substantially such as whooping cough
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pesco2014modelling"

\end_inset

, measles (the incidence of measles decreased by over 98% and the 2â€“3-year
 epidemic cycles no longer occurred) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pang2015transmission"

\end_inset

, influenza 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gross1995efficacy"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Measles was eliminated from U.S.
 since 2002.
 In other countries, especially in developing countries, measles vaccination
 has not extensively popularized.
 Consequently, it is still very important to model the transmission dynamics
 of measles and investigate the effect of vaccination on the spread of measles
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pang2015transmission"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Vaccination, is one of the most effective strategies in preventing morbidity
 and mortality associated with various infectious diseases, has also been
 included in modeling.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The impacts of vaccination policy on the level of vaccination coverage and
 found that voluntary vaccination was unlikely to reach the group-optimal
 level.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Complex dynamics such as oscillations and chaos in measles epidemic models
 and the persistence of disease ars affected by : the population size of
 the community, the spatial structure and connectedness of the regional
 population, and the seasonal forcing.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
