\begin_layout Subsection*
Vaccine allocations about the georaphic:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In order to enact socially optimal vaccination policies, policy-makers not
 only need to be well-informed with regard to infectious disease dynamics,
 but also with regard to vaccination policy analysis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The network structure (The allocation of populations, vaccines) plays an
 important role for the effectiveness of a vaccination policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Wu et.
 al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "wu2007spatial"

\end_inset

 viewed vaccine allocation as a nonlinear optimization problem in which
 the objective was to minimize the total number of infections across a populatio
n.
 The authors proposed two vaccination policies : a portion of the total
 vaccine supply was designated to be distributed pro-rata, which is equitable
 distribution by population, and the other portion of the vaccine supply
 was to be discretionarily distributed.
 The result : the purely equitable distribution was the least efficient
 allocation in terms of minimizing the total number of infections in the
 population.
 The purely discretionary policy is efficient, but highly inequitable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Vaccine allocations about the time side: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Matrajt2010
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "matrajt2010optimizing"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
they used a mathematical model to find the optimal vaccine allocation at
 different time points of an epidemic.
 For both developed and less developed countries, when faced with low supplies
 of vaccines, it is always optimal to concentrate vaccine in high-risk children
 to provide them with direct protection, as they are part of the high-transmissi
on chain and they are among the most vulnerable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
pointed out that : Choosing the optimal strategy before or early in the
 epidemic makes an important difference in minimizing the number of influenza
 infections, and consequently the number of influenza deaths or hospitalizations
, but the optimal strategy makes little difference after the peak.
 When averting deaths, it is better to allocate vaccine in the high-risk
 groups first and then cover high- transmission groups.
 Once vaccine supplies reach a certain coverage level, then it becomes important
 to vaccinate the high- transmission groups in the earlier stages of the
 epidemic, but this policy becomes suboptimal once the peak of the epidemic
 has passed.
 This is because by allocating this much vaccine in children earlier on
 in the epidemic, we would be able to block transmission and mitigate the
 disease, but if vaccination took place later on in the epidemic, there
 are too many people already infected and this strategy is no longer optimal.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection*
Limitation :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A limitation of the network models presented above is that they are all
 specific to disease propagation.
 However, network models applied to more general contexts also provide insight
 into the vaccine allocation problem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The limitation of these framework is that many attributes described in the
 research depend upon a well- defined notion of community structure.
 However, it is exceedingly difficult to detect and distinguish communities
 within a larger network.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In fact, the big differences between perceived risk of infectious disease
 and actual risk of infectious disease.
 Therefore, individuals likely make great errors when making their choices
 for vaccination.
 Thus, these errors must be taken into account when considering policy actions
 to be taken to move toward a socially optimal allocation 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "galvani2007long"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The triple of network structure, disease propagation, and vaccination policy
 are three very important factors to build the network attributes.
 The degree centrality, closeness centrality, betweenness centrality, and
 node significance are important network attributes to consider in context
 of disease spread.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsection
Using the optimal algorithms
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Evolutionary Algorithms (EA) policies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Shaw2010 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "shaw2010effective"

\end_inset

 extended the model to include a supply of vaccine, which is to be distributed
 in an optimal fashion.
 By mathematical analysis of this model, they determined the feasibility
 of a vaccination policy by using the Evolutionary Algorithms (EA), they
 searched for vaccination policies that minimize the number of infected
 people.
 They compared these policies to plausible benchmark policies to verify
 that the EA policies are more effective.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Analysis of the EA policies indicates that the vaccine is generally distributed
 to (1) the city of origin for the virus, (2) cities that are traveled to
 most often, and (3) smaller cities.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection
Convergence in Evolutionary Programs with Self-Adaptation [Greenwood 2001]-
 proposed by YANN
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Reason: 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Evolutionary programs are capable of finding good solutions to difficult
 optimization problems.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Previous analysis of their convergence properties has normally assumed the
 strategy parameters are kept constant, although in practice these parameters
 are dynamically altered.
 - In this paper, we propose a modified version of the 1/5-success rule
 for self-adaptation in evolution strategies (ES).
 Evolutionary programs are probabilistic algorithms that use the principles
 of population genetics to search for problem solutions.
 They are capable of finding good solutions to a wide variety of optimization
 problems, including NP-hard combinatorial optimization problems (Back,
 1996).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Problem 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu+\lambda)-ES$
\end_inset

 : These 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 parents (candidate solutions) produce 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 offspring (new solutions) by mutating one or more problem parameters.
 Parents and offspring compete equally for survival; only the 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 best (i.e., those with the highest fitness) will survive to reproduce in
 the next generation.
 Done properly, the population will evolve towards increasingly better regions
 of the search space by means of reproduction and survival of the ttest.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Problem 
\begin_inset Formula $(\mu,\lambda)-ES$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 parents produce 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 offspring, but only the best 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 offspring survive.
 Thus individuals live for only a single generation regardless of their
 tness level.
 This approach may result in short periods of recession, but it does avoid
 long periods of stagnation.
 [Back 1996]
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Subsubsection
Reinforcement learning in vacination policies - proposed by JEAN Daniel
 Zucker (very complex)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Reinforcement learning, a subfield of artificial intelligence, is the study
 of algorithms that learn how to choose the best actions depending on the
 situation.
 In a reinforcement learning problem the algorithm is not told which actions
 give the best results, but instead it has to interact with the environment
 to learn when and where to take a certain action.
 When the agent has learned about each situation or state of the environment,
 it will arrive at an optimal sequence of actions (Barto and Sutton 1998).
 Instead of finding the best results, we find an optimal result for the
 state of the evironnement at time t.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The optimization of vaccination policies by using the reinforcemnt learning:
 for a given population structure, where and when to vaccinate to minimize
 the number of infected or maximize the probability of global eradication.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
SARSA : State-Action-Reward-State-Action
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
One state at time t : (
\begin_inset Formula $\in N^{4}$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=((s_{1},e_{1},i_{1},r_{1}),(s_{2},e_{2},i_{2},r_{2}),....,(s_{n},e_{n},i_{n},r_{n})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Set of states : 
\begin_inset Formula $N^{4*nbCities}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Action at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, vaccinated or not vaccinated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Sum of rewards of a policy:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{t=0}^{\infty}\gamma^{t}r_{t}=r_{0}+\gamma r_{1}+\gamma^{2}r_{2}+\gamma^{3}r_{3}+....
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This problem is a Markov Decision Process.
 However, the number of states at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 is very big.
 It is the reason for that it is an expensive simulator.
 In this case, we desire an MDP planning algorithm that minimizes the number
 of calls to the simulator, runs in time polynomial in the relevant problem
 parameters, and outputs a policy that is approximately optimal with high
 probability 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "dietterich2013pac"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

